{
  "answer": "In the *Manusmṛti*, the term *saṃskāra* explicitly connotes both the external rite and its inner sanctifying effect: \"With sacred Vedic rites must be performed **the purifying saṃskāra** of the body for the twice-born, from conception onwards, which **sanctifies them** in this life and after death.\"[^1]\n\nHere, the *saṃskāra* is the rite (*purifying* underscores its transformative role), but it also imprints an enduring inner purity or mark on the person, elevating their spiritual state across lifetimes. Rendering it simply as \"rite\" or \"sacrament\" loses this dual sense of refinement: the ceremony *as* the process of inner perfection, akin to a mental-spiritual impression (like a \"conditioning\" or \"imprinting\" that readies one for higher existence). English terms emphasize the ritual act but obscure how the *saṃskāra* inherently *cultivates* an indelible sacred quality in the soul.[^2][^3]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, [Chapter 2, paragraph p-3cd4c5](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76-347b76/02/translation/#p-3cd4c5).\n\n[^2]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, [Chapter 1, paragraph p-3b5116](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-3b5116). (\"Through a new *saṃskāra*, he becomes pure.\")\n\n[^3]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, [Chapter 1, paragraph p-b2f0f2](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-b2f0f2). (Non-performance of *saṃskāras* during *dīkṣā* blocks purity; transgression requires a remedial *saṃskāra*.)",
